article.headline: Arizona State 67, Delaware State 56
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Double- and triple-teaming don't bother Ike Diogu. He just gets his points from the line. Arizona State's junior center had 32 points and nine rebounds, almost singlehandedly lifting the Sun Devils to a 67-56 victory over Delaware State on Tuesday night. Diogu, who set a Pac-10 record with 243 free throws made last season, tied his school record by making 18 this time. His 21 attempts were two short of his standard, set with an 18-for-23 effort against Western Michigan last Dec. 30. Eddie House shares the record, making 18 in a double-overtime game against California on Jan. 8, 2000. "I'm just trying to stay aggressive," Diogu said. "Coaches just kept telling me to be aggressive, that eventually they'd start calling things for me." Reserve Kevin Kruger added 12 points for the Sun Devils (2-0). Jahsha Bluntt scored 17 points for Delaware State (0-3) and Terrance Hunter had 15 and eight rebounds. The Hornets pushed Arizona State throughout the contest, a second round game of the Las Vegas Invitational. Delaware State went on an 11-1 run starting late in the first half to tie it at 36 on Bluntt's two free throws with 18:07 left in the game. After an Arizona State surge, the Hornets closed within 48-45 when Diogu was too late getting back to stop a floor-length in-bounds pass to Hunter for an easy dunk with 11:12 to go. But Diogu started a 14-3 surge with a free throw and dunked 31 seconds later for a 51-45 lead with 10:16 remaining. In a 6:22 span ending with Arizona State leading 65-52 with 2:30 to go, Diogu had a three-point play, another dunk and five free throws. "I've never played against anybody who shot 21 free throws," Hunter said. "It was like, you breathe on him, and beep (whistle). I was trying to throw my body into him and everything. I couldn't get the same calls." Kruger, whose four-point play early the first half brought the Sun Devils from behind to a 15-15 tie, said the tense game was good preparation for conference play. "If it happens to be close, so be it," he said. "We just go out and take charge of what we can control." He and Diogu, who scored in double figures for the 61st consecutive game, had seven points each during a 23-7 run that lifted the Sun Devils to a 32-22 lead with 3:28 left in the first half. Diogu restored the 10-point lead with 1:12 to go, sinking a short left-handed hook shot to make it 35-25. But Delaware State forced two turnovers, and Hunter had two baskets and Bluntt one in the final 36 seconds as the Hornets closed within 35-31 at halftime. The Sun Devils had 23 turnovers in a 79-48 win over Jackson State on Sunday, but coach Rob Evans wasn't worried about loose ballhandling. "We had 15 turnovers and Ike had six of them, so we didn't turn it over; Ike turned it over," Evans said. "But those are all correctible errors." Evans said his team is ready to play a more heralded opponent -- UNLV -- Friday in Las Vegas. "Whether we beat them or not, we'll see," he said.
